:"https://api.github.com/users/claudia-hm/starred{/owner}{/repo}","subscriptions_url":"https://api.github.com/users/claudia-hm/subscriptions","organizations_url":"https://api.github.com/users/claudia-hm/orgs","repos_url":"https://api.github.com/users/claudia-hm/repos","events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/claudia-hm/events{/privacy}","received_events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/claudia-hm/received_events","type":"User","site_admin":false},"created_at":"2022-02-17T11:52:50Z","updated_at":"2022-02-17T11:52:50Z","author_association":"NONE","body":"Hello @fkiraly,\r\n\r\nI've just tried an equivalent code with ```pmdarima``` and yes, I obtain the same behavior.\r\n```python\r\nimport pmdarima as pm\r\nfrom sktime.utils.plotting import plot_series\r\nimport pandas as pd\r\nimport numpy as np\r\nimport matplotlib.pyplot as plt \r\n\r\n#generate data\r\na, b = 0.5, 100\r\ny1 = a*np.arange(0,100)+b\r\nnoise = np.random.normal(y1)\r\ny1 = y1 + noise\r\ny1 = y1 / (10**6)\r\n\r\nwindow = 20\r\ny1_train = pd.Series(y1[:-window], index = pd.Index(np.arange(0, len(y1)-window)))\r\ny1_test = pd.Series(y1[-window:], index = pd.Index(np.arange(len(y1)-window, len(y1))))\r\n\r\n# Fit your model\r\nmodel = pm.auto_arima(y1_train)\r\n\r\n# make your forecasts\r\nforecasts = model.predict(y1_test.shape[0])  # predict N steps into the future\r\ny1_pred = pd.Series(forecasts, index=y1_test.index)\r\nplot_series(y1_train, y1_test, y1_pred, labels=[\"train\", \"test\", \"pred\"])\r\nplt.show()\r\n```\r\n![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/59530433/154475232-47553196-74f5-490b-b669-ffb6927defa5.png)\r\n\r\nI coincide that it has to be some kind of numerical issue. However, maybe there should be some kind of tolerance value that could prevent this behavior. I'll open an issue in the ```pmdarima``` repo.\r\n\r\nThanks!\r\n\r\n","reactions":{"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/sktime/sktime/issues/comments/1042870329/reactions","total_count":0,"+1":0,"-1":0,"laugh":0,